    "narrative": "The Zurich Zebras enter May 3rd with a high-ceiling lineup led by **Pete Crow-Armstrong** (80.98), who profiles as our premier play today. His matchup against the erratic Merrill Kelly is bolstered by an ideal 18% boost from the opposing SP\u2019s skill set and, crucially, favorable winds blowing out to maximize his slugging profile. With the pitcher\u2019s slow delivery providing a distinct advantage for his stolen base upside\u2014our primary target for scarcity\u2014**Pete Crow-Armstrong** is the clear anchor. Following him, **Trea Turner** (69.28) and **Junior Caminero** (71.71) offer excellent efficiency. **Trea Turner** leverages his leadoff spot to capitalize on the 4.41 xERA of Chris Paddack, while **Junior Caminero** benefits from a high-upside matchup against Tyler Mahle, where his platoon advantage and batting order slot provide the optimal conditions for an extra-base hit.\n\nThe most difficult decision for today's lineup centered on **Jerar Encarnacion**, whose score of 42.40 placed him just outside our starting rotation. While **Jerar Encarnacion** offers a platoon edge against Steven Matz, the optimizer favored the higher-floor efficiency of our designated hitters against softer matchups, specifically the favorable 5.19 xERA facing **Carson Benge**. Despite the solid projections for **Jerar Encarnacion**, the volume of R/R matchups across the board squeezed him out. We are also monitoring **Gary Sanchez**, **Dillon Dingler**, **Kazuma Okamoto**, **Colt Keith**, **Chase Meidroth**, and **Kyle Schwarber** closely, as all rely on \"Lineup Pending\" status; any shifts out of the top six in their respective orders will force a re-evaluation of their daily efficiency scores. **Yordan Alvarez** remains a locked-in start despite a challenging L/L matchup against Suarez, as his elite 0.430 xwOBA remains too significant to bench, even when accounting for the slight platoon suppression.",
